```java
import org.junit.Test;
import static org.junit.Assert.*;

public class HelloTest {

    @Test
    public void testGreetNormalName() {
        String name = "Alice";
        String expectedGreeting = "Hello, Alice!";
        String actualGreeting = Hello.greet(name);
        assertEquals(expectedGreeting, actualGreeting);
    }

    @Test
    public void testGreetEmptyName() {
        String name = "";
        String expectedGreeting = "Hello, !";
        String actualGreeting = Hello.greet(name);
        assertEquals(expectedGreeting, actualGreeting);
    }

    @Test
    public void testGreetNullName() {
        String name = null;
        String expectedGreeting = "Hello, null!";
        String actualGreeting = Hello.greet(name);
        assertEquals(expectedGreeting, actualGreeting);
    }
}
```

The tests cover greeting a person with a normal name, an empty string name, and a null name. It validates the expected greeting is returned in each case by comparing it to the actual greeting using JUnit's `assertEquals` assertion. The `greet` method is imported from the `Hello` class to be accessible for testing.

