Here's the completed code for the new unit tests, including the necessary imports:

```java
import org.junit.Test;
import static org.junit.Assert.assertArrayEquals;

public class MergeSortTest {
    private MergeSort mergeSort = new MergeSort();

    @Test
    public void testMergeSort_EvenLength() {
        int[] arr = {5, 2, 8, 1, 9, 3, 7, 4};
        int[] expectedLeft = {5, 2, 8, 1};
        int[] expectedRight = {9, 3, 7, 4};

        mergeSort.mergeSort(arr);

        int[] actualLeft = new int[arr.length / 2];
        int[] actualRight = new int[arr.length / 2];

        for (int i = 0; i < arr.length / 2; i++) {
            actualLeft[i] = arr[i];
        }
        for (int i = arr.length / 2; i < arr.length; i++) {
            actualRight[i - arr.length / 2] = arr[i];
        }

        assertArrayEquals(expectedLeft, actualLeft);
        assertArrayEquals(expectedRight, actualRight);
    }

    @Test
    public void testMergeSort_OddLength() {
        int[] arr = {5, 2, 8, 1, 9, 3, 7};
        int[] expectedLeft = {5, 2, 8};
        int[] expectedRight = {1, 9, 3, 7};

        mergeSort.mergeSort(arr);

        int[] actualLeft = new int[arr.length / 2];
        int[] actualRight = new int[(arr.length + 1) / 2];

        for (int i = 0; i < arr.length / 2; i++) {
            actualLeft[i] = arr[i];
        }
        for (int i = arr.length / 2; i < arr.length; i++) {
            actualRight[i - arr.length / 2] = arr[i];
        }

        assertArrayEquals(expectedLeft, actualLeft);
        assertArrayEquals(expectedRight, actualRight);
    }
}
```

This test suite includes two test cases:

1. `testMergeSort_EvenLength`: Tests the splitting of an array with an even length into left and right subarrays.
2. `testMergeSort_OddLength`: Tests the splitting of an array with an odd length into left and right subarrays.

Both test cases create an input array, call the `mergeSort` method, and then assert that the left and right subarrays are correctly populated based on the expected values.

